    <h2 class="page-title">Depression</h2>
    <div class="content">
        <h3 class="sub-title">About</h3>
        <p>
            Depression is a common mental disorder and one of the main causes of disability. 
            In 2021, there is an estimated 280 million people globally that are affected by depression, with a higher percentage of women being affected.
            This has increased from 264 million in year 2019. 

        </p>

        <h3 class="sub-title">Characteristics</h3>
        <p>
            Some symptoms that one may experience during a depressive episode includes:
            <li>depressed mood (feeling of sadness, irritability, emptyness)</li>
            <li>loss of pleasure </li>
            <li>loss of interest in activities (previously liked as well)</li>
            <li>feelings of guilt</li>
            <li>low self worth</li>
            <li>disturbed sleep or appetite</li>
            <li>tiredness</li>
            <li>poor concentration</li>
            <li> hopelessness about the future</li>
            <li>thoughts about dying or suicide</li>
            for most of the day, nearly every day or for at least two weeks
            
            Some may express their mood changes in the form of bodily symptoms, like pain and fatigue. 
            They may have multiple physical complaints with no apparent physical cause.

            These may be long-lasting or recurrent, substantially impairing one's ability to function at work or school and cope with daily activities.

            A depressive episode can be categorized as mild, moderate or severe depending on the number and
            severity of the symptoms, as well as the impact on the individual's functioning. 
        </p>
        <h3 class="sub-title">Measures</h3>
        <p>
            There are prevention programmes for both adults and children. Some programmes for adults include psychosocial assistance after 
            disasters and conflicts. Some programmes for children include protection and psychological support following physical and sexual abuse. These programmes
            have shown to reduce depression.
        </p>
        <br>
        <p>
            Some medical treatments include:
            <li>Mild to moderate: Treated with talking therapy, such as cognitive behaviour therapy or psychotherapy</li>
            <br>
            Moderate to severe:
            <li>Antidepressants can be an effective form of treatment but not the first line of treatment</li>
            <li>Should not be used to treat depression in children</li>
            <li>Not the first line of treatment in adolescents</li>
        
        </p>
